  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Cry of the Poor and the Cry of the Earth: Amerindia&apos;s strategic plan 2019-2021</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The aim of this project is to continue to &quot;promote the prophetic and liberating engagement of Christians, in fidelity to Jesus Christ, with the poor of Latin America and the Caribbean; an engagement which contributes to the integration and construction of a just society.&#x201D;

Amerindia is a theological network with reach across Latin America and the Caribbean. It has its origins in 1978 when a group of theologians came together to advise the Bishops in preparation for the Puebla Conference. The group did the same for the Santo Domingo Conference in 1992 and again for the Rome Synod in 1997. It was after the Synod that Amerindia developed into a wider network of Bishops, theologians, communicators, educators, social scientists, members of religious congregations, and lay people.  

Its Social and Ecclesial Observatories provide invaluable analysis to underpin theological reflection on current affairs in Latin America and the Caribbean and the response of the Church.  Whilst its roots are in the Catholic Church, Amerindia seeks to be ecumenical, drawing on other Christian traditions, as well as faith traditions of indigenous and African-descendant peoples.  

Following the conclusion of the 3-year framework (2016-2018), Amerindia has developed a new 3-year plan (2019-2021), inspired by the Continental Theological Conference, and in the ongoing belief that another world is possible.  It maintains the same overarching aim for this 3-year period.</narrative>
  </description>
